Introduction

  • Two distinct developments in statistical learning and forecasting
    • Large scale streaming data is becoming ubiquitous in many applications in energy markets, e.g. market prices and renewables forecasts
    • Paradigm shift towards probabablistic forecasting (Nowotarski and Weron 2018)
  • Research Gap
    • Distributional online learning approaches very sparse in the literature
    • Some approaches available (Álvarez, Mazuelas, and Lozano 2021; Werge and Wintenberger 2022; Hendrych and Cipra 2018; Cipra and Hendrych 2018; Dahlhaus and Subba Rao 2007)
  • Contribution
    • Implement an online, regularized, linear parametric GAMLSS model
    • Open-source Python package implementation
    • Forecasting study for day-ahead electricity prices

Method

Cyclic Coordinate Descent

  • Update the coefficients in the weighted LASSO estimation by repeatetly updating all \(\beta_j\) for \(j = 0, ..., J\) explanatory variables (Friedman et al. 2007; Friedman, Hastie, and Tibshirani 2010). \[\begin{equation} %\beta_j \xleftarrow{} \frac{S\left( \sum_{n=1}^{N} w_n x_{n,j}(y_n - \tilde{y}_n^{(j)}), \lambda \cdot \alpha \right)}{\sum_{n=1}^{N} w_n x_{n,j}^2 + \lambda ( 1 - \alpha)} %including elastic net \beta_j \xleftarrow{} \frac{S\left( \sum_{n=1}^{N} w_n x_{n,j}(y_n - \tilde{y}_n^{(j)}), \lambda \right)}{\sum_{n=1}^{N} w_n x_{n,j}^2}\label{eq_lasso_update} % + \lambda ( 1 - \alpha)} % LASSO only \end{equation}\]
  • For a given regularizeation parameter \(\lambda\), explanatory variables \(x_{n,j}\),
  • \(S(\hat{\beta}, \lambda) = \text{sign}(\hat{\beta})(\lvert \hat{\beta} \rvert - \lambda)_+\) is the soft-thresholding function.

Online Coordinate Descent

  • We can reformulate the problem to use the Gramia matrices \({\mathcal{G}}= {\mathcal{X}}^\top \Gamma {\mathcal{W}}{\mathcal{X}}\) and \({\mathcal{H}}= {\mathcal{X}}^\top \Gamma {\mathcal{W}}{\mathcal{Y}}\), where \({\mathcal{W}}\) is an arbitrary weight matrix and \(\Gamma\) is a weight matrix with exponential forget (Angelosante, Bazerque, and Giannakis 2010; Messner and Pinson 2019). \[\begin{equation} \beta_j \xleftarrow{} \frac{% %S\left(\HH\left[j\right] - \GG\left[j, :\right] \bsbeta + \GG\left[j, j\right]\beta_j, \lambda \cdot \alpha \right) S\left({\mathcal{H}}\left[j\right] - {\mathcal{G}}\left[j, :\right] \boldsymbol \beta+ {\mathcal{G}}\left[j, j\right]\beta_j, \lambda \right) }{% %\GG\left[j, j\right] + \lambda ( 1 - \alpha) {\mathcal{G}}\left[j, j\right] } \label{eq_update_dep_gram} \end{equation}\]
  • Update of the Gramian matrices with new data is straight-forward: \[\begin{align} {\mathcal{G}}_{n+1} &= \gamma{\mathcal{G}}_{n} + w_{n+1}(\boldsymbol X^\top_{n+1} \boldsymbol X_{n+1}) \label{eq:update_gramian_g} \\ {\mathcal{H}}_{n+1} &= \gamma{\mathcal{H}}_{n} + w_{n+1}(\boldsymbol X^\top_{n+1} \boldsymbol Y_{n+1}) \label{eq:update_gramian_h} \end{align}\]
  • Warm-start of the online coordinate descent using the \(\beta\)-path of the previous estimation \(\beta_n\) for \(\beta_{n+1}\).

Online GAMLSS: Setting

  • The response variable \({\mathcal{Y}}\) have PDF \(f_\mathcal{Y} \left(y_i \mid \mu_i, \sigma_i, \nu_i, \tau_i \right)\) and hence distributed \[\begin{equation} \mathcal{Y}_i \sim \mathcal{D}\left(\mu_i, \sigma_i, \nu_i, \tau_i \right) \Leftrightarrow \mathcal{D}\left(\theta_{i,1}, \theta_{i,2}, \theta_{i,3}, \theta_{i,4} \right) \end{equation}\]
  • Linear parametric GAMLSS setting \[\begin{equation} g_k(\theta_k) = \boldsymbol \eta_k = {\mathcal{X}}^k\boldsymbol \beta_k \end{equation}\] where
    • \({\mathcal{X}}^k\) is a known design matrix,
    • \(\boldsymbol \beta_k = (\beta_{k, 1}, ...., \beta_{k, J_k})^\top\) is a coefficient vector of length \(J_k\)
    • \({\theta_k = (\theta_{0,k}, \theta_{1,k}, ..., \theta_{n,k})}\) is the vector of distribution parameters
    • \(g_k(\cdot)\) is a known, monotonic link function relating a distribution parameter to a predictor \(\boldsymbol \eta_k\)
  • Allows for fitting linear models for all (conditional) distribution parameters (Rigby and Stasinopoulos 2005; Stasinopoulos et al. 2024)

Online GAMLSS: Scoring and Working Vector

  • We have the likelihood \({\mathcal{L}}_{\mathcal{D}}\) and \(l_{\mathcal{D}}\) log-likelihood function of the distribution \({\mathcal{D}}\) given the data \(Y_i\), \(l(Y \mid \boldsymbol \theta)\), where \(\boldsymbol \theta= (\theta_1, ..., \theta_k)\) for \(k\) distribution parameters.
  • The score function \(\boldsymbol u_k = { \frac{\partial l}{\partial \theta_k} } / { \frac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_k}{\partial \theta_k} }\)
  • The adjusted dependent variable \(\boldsymbol z_k = \boldsymbol \eta_k + \boldsymbol W_{kk}^{-1}\boldsymbol u_k\)
  • The weight martrix \(\boldsymbol W_{kk}\) is a diagonal, iterative weight matrix \[\begin{equation}\label{eq:gamlss_weight} \boldsymbol W_{ks} = - { \frac{\partial^2 l}{\partial \theta_k} } / { \left(\frac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_k}{\partial \theta_k} \left(\dfrac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_s}{\partial \theta_s}\right)^\top\right) } \end{equation}\]
  • And hence the observation vector \(\boldsymbol z_k\) reads: \[\begin{equation}\label{eq:gamlss_working_vector} \boldsymbol z_k = \boldsymbol \eta_k + { \dfrac{\partial l}{\partial \theta_k} } / { \left( \boldsymbol W_{kk} \left(\dfrac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_k}{\partial \theta_k}\right) \right) } = \boldsymbol \eta_k + { \dfrac{\partial l}{\partial \theta_k} } / { \left( - { \dfrac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_k}{\partial \theta_k} \left(\dfrac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_s}{\partial \theta_s}\right)^\top } / { \dfrac{\partial^2 l}{\partial \theta_k} } \right) \left(\dfrac{\partial \boldsymbol \eta_k}{\partial \theta_k}\right) } \end{equation}\]
  • Iterative, weighted of fit \(\boldsymbol z_k\) on design \({\mathcal{X}}_K\) using \(\boldsymbol W_{kk}\). \(\rightarrow\) agnostic to regression technique.

Online GAMLSS: Algorithm

  1. Initialise the fitted values \(\theta_{k, n+1}^{[0, 0]} = \boldsymbol \beta_{k, n}\boldsymbol X^\top_{k, n+1}\) and the linear predictors \({\eta^{[0, 0]}_{k, n+1} = g_k(\theta_{k, n+1}^{[0, 0]})}\).
  2. Start the outer cycle \(m = 0, 1, ...\) until convergence. Iterate over \(k = 1, ...., p\) and
    • Start the inner cycle \(n = 0, 1, ...\) until convergence:
      • Evaluate \(u_{n+1, k}^{[m,r]}\), \(w_{n+1, kk}^{[m,r]}\) and \(z_{n+1, k}^{[m,r]}\) and update \({\mathcal{G}}_{k, n} \rightarrow {\mathcal{G}}_{k, n+1}^{[m, r]}\) and \({\mathcal{H}}_{k, n} \rightarrow {\mathcal{H}}_{k, n+1}^{[m, r]}\).
      • Update the coefficient path \(\boldsymbol \beta_{n, k, \lambda}^{[m,r]} \rightarrow \boldsymbol \beta_{n, k, \lambda}^{[m,r+1]}\) using OCD based on \({\mathcal{G}}_{k, n+1}^{[m, r]}\) and \({\mathcal{H}}_{k, n+1}^{[m, r]}\) and select the optimal tuning parameter \(\lambda\) using IC. Update the RSS.
    • Calculate the updated \(\boldsymbol \eta_{k, n+1}^{[m, r+1]}\) and \(\boldsymbol \theta_{k, n+1}^{[m, r+1]}\) and evaluate the convergence.
    • End the inner cycle on the convergence of \(\boldsymbol \beta_{k, n+1}^{[m, ...]}\) and set starting values for next outer cycle. Otherwise, continue the inner cycle until convergence.
  3. Update \(k\) upon convergence and end the outer cycle if the change in the penalized likelihood is sufficiently small, otherwise update \(m\) and continue the outer cycle.

Online GAMLSS: Caveats

  • The weight matrix for past observations does not get updated.
    • In the online setting, \({\mathcal{W}}_{kk, n}\) is the weight matrix after convergence of update step \(n-1 \rightarrow n\).
    • In the update step \(n \rightarrow n+1\), we cannot update \({\mathcal{W}}_{kk, n}\) anymore. Therefore, we set \[{\mathcal{W}}_{kk, n+1}^{[m,r]} = \begin{pmatrix} (1-\gamma){\mathcal{W}}_{kk, n} & 0 \\ 0 & w_{kk, n+1}^{[m,r]} \end{pmatrix}\] and can only update \(w_{kk, n+1}^{[m,r]}\).
  • Is this bad?
    • For i.i.d observations with fixed coefficients and, we should achieve worse convergence towards the true parameters.
    • For “real data” with changes in the DGP, structural breaks etc, we can’t say.
  • Exponential forgetting might counteract this effect.
  • Online GAMLSS approximation

Forecasting Study for Day-Ahead Electricity Prices

Forecasting Study: Expert Models

  • Day-ahead electricty prices for Germany
  • Data from ENTSO-E and
  • Expert type models as common in EPF literature: \[\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \label{eq:model} g_k(\theta^k_{d, h}) &= \beta_{k, 0, h} + \beta_{k, 1, h} P_{d-1, h} + \beta_{k, 2, h} P_{d-2, h} + \beta_{k, 3, h} P_{d-7, h} + \beta_{k, 4, h} P_{d-14, h} \\ %P_{d,h} &+ \sum_{s \in \{0, 1, ..., H\} \setminus h} \beta_{5+s, k, h} P_{d-1, k} + \beta_{k, 29, h} \widehat{\operatorname{Load}}_{d, h} + \beta_{k, 30, h} \widehat{\operatorname{RES}}_{d, h} \\ &+ \beta_{k, 31, h} \operatorname{EUA}_{d} + \beta_{k, 32, h} \operatorname{Gas}_{d} + \beta_{k, 33, h} \operatorname{Coal}_{d, h} + \beta_{k, 34, h} \operatorname{Oil}_{d} \\ &+ \beta_{k, 35, h} \operatorname{Mon}_{d, h} + \beta_{k, 36, h} \operatorname{Sat}_{d, h} + \beta_{k, 37, h} \operatorname{Sun}_{d, h} \\ \end{aligned} \end{equation}\]
  • Model coefficients can be grouped in 4 main groups:
    • Price effects (autoregressive + cross-periods)
    • Fundamental forecasts for renewables and demand
    • Fundamental prices (Gas, Coal, Oil, EUA)
    • Weekday effekts

Diebold-Mariano Test

  • \(p\)-value < 0.05 implies that model on the column has significantly better forecasting performance than model on the row
  • CRPS scoring rule used in the DM-test’s loss differential
  • Batch JSU model performs best
  • Online models can have significantly better forecasting accurarcy than batch counterparts

Implementation

ondil Python Package

Implementation of a straight-forward Python package with familiar, consistent API

import ondil
import numpy as np
from sklearn.datasets import load_diabetes

X, y = load_diabetes(return_X_y=True) # Add an intercept
X = np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0], 1)), X))

online_gamlss_lasso = ondil.OnlineGamlss(
    distribution=ondil.T(), 
    method="lasso", 
    estimation_kwargs={"ic" : "bic"}
)
## Fit all observations excluding the last
online_gamlss_lasso.fit(
    y=y[:-1], 
    x0=X[:-1, :], # location
    x1=X[:-1, :], # scale
    x2=X[:-1, :] # tail
)
## Update to include the last observation
online_gamlss_lasso.update(
    y=y[[-1]], 
    x0=X[[-1], :], 
    x1=X[[-1], :], 
    x2=X[[-1], :]
)

Conclusion

Conclusion and further research

  • Developed an computationally efficient online distributional regression model
    • Validated our implementation with a forecasting study for day-ahead electricity prices
    • Online / incremental models delivery competitive performance
  • Next steps
    • Online model selection - some further work on global vs. local selection
    • Analysis of consistency in a simulation study
    • Improve ondil package further: Documentation, more distributions, …
  • Future research
    • Splines and non-linear effects (some splines are simple by extending \(X\), automatic online knot selection seems more complicated)
    • Theoretical results on error bounds
